data.value: Self-driving vehicles are rapidly emerging across North America, they promise safer, more efficient transportation. Harsh weather, in particular snow, rain, and mist, are all significant challenges for self-driving vehicles. Self-driving vehicles rely heavily on sensors such as LiDAR, radar, and cameras, which can be affected by weather. Besides the obvious, like rain or mist simply blocking the line of sight of the sensors, snow, for instance, can obscure road markings making it difficult to determine which part of the road you are on. This could even lead to vehicles slowing down or pulling over in particularly severe weather. How can self-driving technology be improved to provide safe and reliable operation in difficult weather conditions, particularly in regions like Canada and North America, where snow and bad weather are common?
